00:05:54.510 --> 00:05:56.062
- [Derek] So the yellow is the input?

00:05:56.062 --> 00:05:57.360
- [David] Yellow is the input.

00:05:57.360 --> 00:05:58.620
Purple is the output.

00:05:58.620 --> 00:06:00.247
We have essentially a two-volt change

00:06:00.247 --> 00:06:02.250
on the input giving us, what is this?

00:06:02.250 --> 00:06:06.360
Five volts, so five, 10,
15-volt change on the output.

00:06:06.360 --> 00:06:07.680
- [Derek] For this demonstration,

00:06:07.680 --> 00:06:10.290
we were only using 24 volts on the anode.

00:06:10.290 --> 00:06:11.820
If we had used a higher voltage,

00:06:11.820 --> 00:06:14.520
we could have got a lot more amplification

00:06:14.520 --> 00:06:16.650
and people did.

00:06:16.650 --> 00:06:18.660
This was the device that allowed us

00:06:18.660 --> 00:06:21.390
to call long distance for the first time.

00:06:21.390 --> 00:06:22.440
Using vacuum tubes,

00:06:22.440 --> 00:06:23.972
the first transcontinental call

00:06:23.972 --> 00:06:25.830
from New York to San Francisco

00:06:25.830 --> 00:06:29.433
took place on the 25th of January, 1915.

00:06:31.710 --> 00:06:33.000
- [Derek] Whoa.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:34.290
- [David] Yeah, there we go,

00:06:34.290 --> 00:06:36.090
should be 10 volts.

00:06:36.090 --> 00:06:37.736
- [Derek] It's hard to see the grid here

00:06:37.736 --> 00:06:40.980
because just like with
the cylindrical diode,

00:06:40.980 --> 00:06:42.488
the best configuration for a triode

00:06:42.488 --> 00:06:45.120
is to have a cylindrical configuration.

00:06:45.120 --> 00:06:46.378
The anode is on the outside,

00:06:46.378 --> 00:06:48.361
the grid is cylindrically inside that,

00:06:48.361 --> 00:06:51.483
and the cathode or
filament is in the center.

00:06:52.530 --> 00:06:55.140
The invention of the triode
was incredibly important.

00:06:55.140 --> 00:06:58.830
Radios, TVs, whatever
electronics people had

00:06:58.830 --> 00:07:00.810
were powered by vacuum tubes.

00:07:00.810 --> 00:07:02.730
You would've had so many in your house

00:07:02.730 --> 00:07:05.760
even up until the 1960s and '70s.

00:07:05.760 --> 00:07:09.303
But vacuum tubes weren't done
revolutionizing electronics.

00:07:10.500 --> 00:07:12.630
In his 1937 thesis,

00:07:12.630 --> 00:07:15.810
Claude Shannon found a connection
between electric circuits

00:07:15.810 --> 00:07:19.410
and a branch of mathematics
known as Boolean algebra.

00:07:19.410 --> 00:07:21.390
Working in the mid-1800s,

00:07:21.390 --> 00:07:23.340
George Boole was trying to find

00:07:23.340 --> 00:07:25.710
a mathematical foundation for logic.

00:07:25.710 --> 00:07:26.730
Under his system,

00:07:26.730 --> 00:07:28.320
a true statement was represented

00:07:28.320 --> 00:07:31.380
as a 1 and a false statement as a 0.

00:07:31.380 --> 00:07:35.340
And Boole also developed
a few operations like AND.

00:07:35.340 --> 00:07:37.423
If both statements A and B were true,

00:07:37.423 --> 00:07:40.143
then the output would also be true.

00:07:41.310 --> 00:07:43.920
What Shannon realized is
that Boole's operations

00:07:43.920 --> 00:07:46.620
could be represented
as electronic circuits,

00:07:46.620 --> 00:07:48.090
that there was an equivalence

00:07:48.090 --> 00:07:50.190
between mathematical statements

00:07:50.190 --> 00:07:51.990
and electric circuits.

00:07:51.990 --> 00:07:55.110
All you needed to realize these
circuits in the real world

00:07:55.110 --> 00:07:56.823
were a couple switches.

00:07:57.780 --> 00:07:59.820
That same year, 1937,

00:07:59.820 --> 00:08:02.910
George Stibitz built the
first digital calculator.

00:08:02.910 --> 00:08:06.330
It could add two 1-bit binary numbers.

00:08:06.330 --> 00:08:08.250
That is it could add two numbers

00:08:08.250 --> 00:08:11.070
so long as they were either 0 or 1.

00:08:11.070 --> 00:08:13.500
The calculator worked using a relay,

00:08:13.500 --> 00:08:16.500
that electromechanical
switch from telegraphy.

00:08:16.500 --> 00:08:17.880
There were two inputs.

00:08:17.880 --> 00:08:20.520
If they were left open, the input was 0.

00:08:20.520 --> 00:08:22.770
If closed, it was a 1.

00:08:22.770 --> 00:08:25.283
The output was shown with two light bulbs.

00:08:25.283 --> 00:08:26.970
If no lights were on,

00:08:26.970 --> 00:08:28.260
the answer was 0.

00:08:28.260 --> 00:08:29.730
If the output light was on,

00:08:29.730 --> 00:08:30.810
the answer was 1.

00:08:30.810 --> 00:08:32.100
And if the carry light was on,

00:08:32.100 --> 00:08:33.630
the answer was a 2.

00:08:33.630 --> 00:08:36.690
The circuit diagram works like this.

00:08:36.690 --> 00:08:39.420
If neither switch A or B is closed,

00:08:39.420 --> 00:08:41.250
so adding 0 + 0,

00:08:41.250 --> 00:08:43.440
then no current flows through the circuit

00:08:43.440 --> 00:08:45.600
and no light bulb would light up.

00:08:45.600 --> 00:08:47.550
But if input A was closed,

00:08:47.550 --> 00:08:49.200
the current would flow
through the solenoid,

00:08:49.200 --> 00:08:50.820
creating a magnetic field

00:08:50.820 --> 00:08:53.460
that pulls the switch inside it closed,

00:08:53.460 --> 00:08:55.845
and this connects the
output light bulb to power

00:08:55.845 --> 00:08:58.020
and disconnects the carry light bulb.

00:08:58.020 --> 00:09:00.510
So the output light bulb lights up,

00:09:00.510 --> 00:09:02.430
meaning that the answer is 1.

00:09:02.430 --> 00:09:03.540
And the same thing would happen

00:09:03.540 --> 00:09:07.050
when input B was closed and A was open.

00:09:07.050 --> 00:09:09.609
But if you closed both
A and B simultaneously,

00:09:09.609 --> 00:09:13.110
then there is no current
flowing through the solenoid

00:09:13.110 --> 00:09:14.970
but there would be a current flowing

00:09:14.970 --> 00:09:16.248
from the battery connected to A,

00:09:16.248 --> 00:09:18.720
which is connected to
the carry light bulb.

00:09:18.720 --> 00:09:23.070
So it lights up indicating 1 + 1 equals 2.

00:09:23.070 --> 00:09:25.239
This is the beginning of the digital age,

00:09:25.239 --> 00:09:27.630
and no it was not glamorous.

00:09:27.630 --> 00:09:30.539
Stibitz built his device
out of a few batteries,

00:09:30.539 --> 00:09:33.630
light bulbs, and relays
he had lying around.

00:09:33.630 --> 00:09:37.050
And for the inputs, he
cut up a tin of tobacco.

00:09:37.050 --> 00:09:39.450
He built it in one night
at his kitchen table

00:09:39.450 --> 00:09:42.720
which is why it became
known as the Model K.

00:09:42.720 --> 00:09:44.160
The circuit that Stibitz built

00:09:44.160 --> 00:09:46.560
is now called a half adder.

00:09:46.560 --> 00:09:47.910
But if you look at the circuit

00:09:47.910 --> 00:09:49.650
through the eyes of Claude Shannon,

00:09:49.650 --> 00:09:53.280
you realize it's actually
a pair of logic gates.

00:09:53.280 --> 00:09:55.290
The output light bulb should turn on

00:09:55.290 --> 00:09:59.460
when either A or B, but
not both, are closed,

00:09:59.460 --> 00:10:02.850
so this is known as an exclusive OR gate.

00:10:02.850 --> 00:10:04.890
Whereas the carry light
bulb should only turn on

00:10:04.890 --> 00:10:07.034
when both A and B are closed,

00:10:07.034 --> 00:10:10.140
so this is an AND gate.

00:10:10.140 --> 00:10:12.300
This circuit uses electrical versions

00:10:12.300 --> 00:10:15.570
of Boolean operators, XOR and AND.

00:10:15.570 --> 00:10:17.790
And it's possible to build
other Boolean operators

00:10:17.790 --> 00:10:18.742
as electronic gates

00:10:18.742 --> 00:10:22.470
for things like OR, NOR, and NAND.

00:10:22.470 --> 00:10:24.930
And you might say, what's the big deal?

00:10:24.930 --> 00:10:26.640
I mean, the big deal is
that you just tricked

00:10:26.640 --> 00:10:29.160
a bunch of electrons
into doing math for you.

00:10:29.160 --> 00:10:30.927
Sure, it's very simple math,

00:10:30.927 --> 00:10:33.570
but you could connect a bunch
of these half adders together

00:10:33.570 --> 00:10:35.526
and build more and more
complicated circuits

00:10:35.526 --> 00:10:38.340
that could do more complex math,

00:10:38.340 --> 00:10:40.080
which is exactly what Stibitz

00:10:40.080 --> 00:10:42.270
and his colleagues at Bell Labs did.

00:10:42.270 --> 00:10:44.550
Two years later, they built the model I,

00:10:44.550 --> 00:10:46.680
which had more than 400 relays

00:10:46.680 --> 00:10:48.960
and could add two eight
digit numbers together

00:10:48.960 --> 00:10:50.490
in a 10th of a second.

00:10:50.490 --> 00:10:52.590
It could also multiply eight digit numbers

00:10:52.590 --> 00:10:54.870
and do multiplication of complex numbers,

00:10:54.870 --> 00:10:57.420
though these more complicated
operations took longer,

00:10:57.420 --> 00:10:59.550
about a minute per calculation.

00:10:59.550 --> 00:11:01.909
