Eight plus eight is 16 in binary,

00:11:46.419 --> 00:11:49.713
which would be 1 0 0 0 0.

00:11:50.576 --> 00:11:52.350
(machine clacking)

00:11:52.350 --> 00:11:54.990
This is essentially a
1-bit arithmetic unit.

00:11:54.990 --> 00:11:56.250
There's no logic functions.

00:11:56.250 --> 00:11:57.780
It only ever does add.

00:11:57.780 --> 00:12:00.026
Now, let's say we wanna do 5 - 2,

00:12:00.026 --> 00:12:01.560
the answer's gonna be 3.

00:12:01.560 --> 00:12:02.850
So we flip this little switch here

00:12:02.850 --> 00:12:05.340
that lets me know that I'm
doing a subtraction operation

00:12:05.340 --> 00:12:08.190
and we do subtraction
by doing 2's complement.

00:12:08.190 --> 00:12:09.180
So essentially what we're doing

00:12:09.180 --> 00:12:11.580
is we're inverting one of the operands

00:12:11.580 --> 00:12:13.200
and we're adding one.

00:12:13.200 --> 00:12:14.181
So now when I run it,

00:12:14.181 --> 00:12:15.720
(machine clacking)

00:12:15.720 --> 00:12:18.209
we can see 5 - 2 is equal to 3,

00:12:18.209 --> 00:12:20.105
so 2 and 1 is 3.

00:12:20.105 --> 00:12:22.210
Now, because of the way that we do this,

00:12:22.210 --> 00:12:23.468
the final carry flag

00:12:23.468 --> 00:12:25.560
ends up getting illuminated
here on the end.

00:12:25.560 --> 00:12:28.650
But if we know that we're
doing a subtraction operation,

00:12:28.650 --> 00:12:30.030
we know that this final carry flag

00:12:30.030 --> 00:12:32.940
is never going to be on otherwise.

00:12:32.940 --> 00:12:34.050
- [Derek] Over the next 10 years,

00:12:34.050 --> 00:12:36.630
they built six more
computers based on relays

00:12:36.630 --> 00:12:38.520
which were used by the US military

00:12:38.520 --> 00:12:40.080
and the National Advisory Committee

00:12:40.080 --> 00:12:42.660
for Astronautics or NACA,

00:12:42.660 --> 00:12:44.970
which later would become NASA.

00:12:44.970 --> 00:12:46.514
But even by the early 1940s,

00:12:46.514 --> 00:12:49.500
it was clear that the
mechanical nature of the relay,

00:12:49.500 --> 00:12:52.260
the physical closing and
opening of the switches,

00:12:52.260 --> 00:12:55.140
was too slow to be the future of computers

00:12:55.140 --> 00:12:57.030
and they were also prone to breaking.

00:12:57.030 --> 00:12:58.650
- Anytime you have
something that's mechanical,

00:12:58.650 --> 00:13:00.030
it's gonna wear down.

00:13:00.030 --> 00:13:02.040
Every time that relay switches,

00:13:02.040 --> 00:13:03.270
there's a little bit of friction

00:13:03.270 --> 00:13:05.550
on the rotation point inside of there

00:13:05.550 --> 00:13:07.260
and there's contacts

00:13:07.260 --> 00:13:09.390
that are making and breaking
electrical connections,

00:13:09.390 --> 00:13:10.590
and those are gonna wear out.

00:13:10.590 --> 00:13:12.690
- [Derek] And all the
relays opening and closing

00:13:12.690 --> 00:13:15.678
meant that the computers
were incredibly loud.

00:13:15.678 --> 00:13:18.960
(machine clacking)

00:13:18.960 --> 00:13:20.820
- So it doesn't really work

00:13:20.820 --> 00:13:22.500
in a business environment all that well.

00:13:22.500 --> 00:13:24.552
You can't really stuff it into your office

00:13:24.552 --> 00:13:26.452
that you're gonna drive people insane.

00:13:28.320 --> 00:13:30.180
- [Derek] So what computer
scientists really needed

00:13:30.180 --> 00:13:32.070
was an electronic switch

00:13:32.070 --> 00:13:35.253
and that is where the
vacuum tube triode comes in.

00:13:36.150 --> 00:13:36.983
Whoa!

00:13:39.030 --> 00:13:40.931
I mean, sure it can work as an amplifier

00:13:40.931 --> 00:13:42.448
if you put slightly positive

00:13:42.448 --> 00:13:44.850
or negative voltages on the grid,

00:13:44.850 --> 00:13:47.520
but it can also work as a switch.

00:13:47.520 --> 00:13:49.920
If the grid voltage is very negative,

00:13:49.920 --> 00:13:51.480
then no current flows.

00:13:51.480 --> 00:13:53.880
And if the grid voltage is very positive,

00:13:53.880 --> 00:13:56.040
then maximum current flows.

00:13:56.040 --> 00:13:58.140
So a triode can be controlled

00:13:58.140 --> 00:14:00.360
using no moving parts.

00:14:00.360 --> 00:14:02.160
Just a voltage will set it

00:14:02.160 --> 00:14:04.680
to be either a 0 or a 1.

00:14:04.680 --> 00:14:06.540
And best of all, switching between the two

00:14:06.540 --> 00:14:09.450
can be done rapidly with no noise

00:14:09.450 --> 00:14:10.938
since you're just controlling electrons

00:14:10.938 --> 00:14:13.500
zipping around in a vacuum.

00:14:13.500 --> 00:14:16.683
This is the invention that took
computing to the next level.

00:14:18.060 --> 00:14:20.430
The world's first electronic
programmable computer

00:14:20.430 --> 00:14:21.690
was called ENIAC

00:14:21.690 --> 00:14:23.310
and it came online for the first time

00:14:23.310 --> 00:14:25.830
on December 10th, 1945.

00:14:25.830 --> 00:14:29.340
It took up a whole room, weighed 30 tons,

00:14:29.340 --> 00:14:33.000
and used 175 kilowatts of power.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:34.579
So much that it led to a rumor

00:14:34.579 --> 00:14:35.997
that every time it turned on,

00:14:35.997 --> 00:14:37.306
the lights in Philadelphia,

00:14:37.306 --> 00:14:40.503
where ENIAC was located, would dim.

00:14:41.850 --> 00:14:43.230
Now, that was just a rumor,

00:14:43.230 --> 00:14:44.820
but mainly because ENIAC

00:14:44.820 --> 00:14:46.604
had its own dedicated electrical generator

00:14:46.604 --> 00:14:50.220
to keep up with the enormous power draw.

00:14:50.220 --> 00:14:51.720
Unlike previous computers,

00:14:51.720 --> 00:14:52.680
ENIAC wasn't limited

00:14:52.680 --> 00:14:55.740
to just solving one type
of mathematical problem.

00:14:55.740 --> 00:14:58.440
It could be programmed and it was fast,

00:14:58.440 --> 00:15:01.860
completing 500 operations per second.

00:15:01.860 --> 00:15:03.480
At the time, the word computers

00:15:03.480 --> 00:15:04.545
still referred to people

00:15:04.545 --> 00:15:07.470
doing calculations with pen and paper.

00:15:07.470 --> 00:15:11.970
So 500 operations per
second was really fast.

00:15:11.970 --> 00:15:13.890
ENIAC's flexibility and power

00:15:13.890 --> 00:15:15.180
was immediately useful

00:15:15.180 --> 00:15:17.430
for the development of the hydrogen bomb.

00:15:17.430 --> 00:15:19.710
The computations needed were so complex

00:15:19.710 --> 00:15:21.510
that the director of
Los Alamos at the time

00:15:21.510 --> 00:15:23.280
said that, "It would've been impossible

00:15:23.280 --> 00:15:24.930
to arrive at any solution

00:15:24.930 --> 00:15:27.390
without the aid of ENIAC."

